# UI/UX — No Unilateral Product Decisions

For **anything that affects what users see, read, tap, or how screens behave**
(Flutter widgets, navigation, copy, labels, layout order, defaults, optional vs
required fields, empty states, validation gates, accessibility affordances, HTML
mocks, ARB strings):

## Hard rule

**Do not take initiative** on product choices the user did not specify. When a
reasonable implementation could go more than one way, **stop and ask in chat**
(in plain text — see `agent-scope-discipline.mdc`) — **before** editing UI code,
ARB files, or routes.

This complements `agent-scope-discipline.mdc` (multi-state scope) and
`ui-restoration-no-new-variants.mdc` (regressions). This rule applies even to
**small** additions (one field, one label, one button state).

## Must ask when unspecified (non-exhaustive)

| Topic | Do not guess |
| --- | --- |
| **Required vs optional** | Whether a field, photo, or step blocks save/submit |
| **Defaults** | Initial switch value, pre-selected dropdown, placeholder text |
| **Order and grouping** | Field order, sections, dividers, what sits above/below what |
| **Labels and copy** | Wording, title casing, “Journal — …” prefixes, helper text |
| **Validation UX** | Snackbar vs inline error, when the primary button disables |
| **Empty / missing data** | Hide row, show “—”, omit section, or block navigation |
| **Navigation** | Push vs go, which screen opens, back-stack behavior |
| **Visual design** | Colors, opacity, fullscreen fit (cover vs contain), bar style |
| **Referenced UI anchor missing** | See below — do not invent the anchor |

## Referenced anchor missing (verify before implementing)

When the user describes placement relative to an **existing** control (“sous le
bouton X”, “à côté de Y”, “comme sur l’écran Z”), **read the target screen in
code first** (or the file they named).

If that control **is not** on that screen at that location:

1. **Do not** add the missing control so the relative placement “makes sense”.
2. **Do not** treat the user’s spatial reference as an implicit request to
   create the anchor.
3. **Stop and ask** one short question: which screen/attachment is the real
   target, or whether they meant a different surface (e.g. hub vs détail véhicule).
4. Implement **only** what they explicitly asked for **once** the anchor is
   confirmed — e.g. add “Lecture d’odomètre” where they want it, without
   backfilling “Achat de carburant” unless they confirm.

A wrong spatial reference usually means the user misspoke; filling in missing UI
from that reference ships **their mistake** as product behavior.

## Allowed without asking

- Match **existing patterns in the same screen or feature** when the user’s
  request already implies them (e.g. “same as fuel purchase form” → reuse that
  widget and behavior).
- Apply **project rules** already binding (terminology dictionary, date/money
  display, melos workflow) — not new product choices.
- **Bug fixes** where expected behavior is **proven** by code, logs, or an
  explicit user correction (“c’est sous le menu Android” → fix placement only).

## When the user confirms

Implement exactly what they chose. Do not add adjacent UX “improvements” in the
same diff unless they asked.

## If you already guessed wrong

Acknowledge briefly, apply the user’s correction, and do not defend the earlier
assumption.
